GREEK 1.description: Lecture, three hours; discussion, two hours. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 1.title: Elementary Greek

GREEK 100.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 20. Introduction to developing skills of reading longer, continuous passes of original Greek prose and/or poetry texts, with attention to literary and cultural background. Course is normally requisite to other courses in Greek 100 series. May be repeated for credit with change of assigned readings and with consent of instructor. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 100.title: Readings in Greek Prose and Poetry

GREEK 101A.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 101A.title: Homer: Odyssey

GREEK 101B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 101B.title: Homer: Iliad

GREEK 102.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Selections from Archilochus to Bacchylides. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 102.title: Lyric Poets

GREEK 103.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 103.title: Aeschylus

GREEK 104.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 104.title: Sophocles

GREEK 105.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 105.title: Euripides

GREEK 106.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 106.title: Aristophanes

GREEK 107.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Reading of "Theogony" and excerpts from "Works and Days," with emphasis on Hesiod's place in Greek literature and his role in transmission of Greek mythology. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 107.title: Hesiod

GREEK 110.description: Lecture, three to four hours. Requisite: course 100. Work in sight reading and grammatical analysis of Attic prose texts; writing Attic prose. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 110.title: Study of Greek Prose

GREEK 111.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 111.title: Herodotus

GREEK 112.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 112.title: Thucydides

GREEK 113.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 113.title: Attic Orators

GREEK 115.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Reading of one major work of Xenophon -- "Memorabilia," "Cyropaedia," "Anabasis," "Hellenica," or "Oeconomicus" -- in Greek. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 115.title: Xenophon

GREEK 121.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 121.title: Plato

GREEK 122.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 122.title: Plato: Republic

GREEK 123.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 123.title: Aristotle: Poetics and Rhetoric

GREEK 124.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 124.title: Aristotle: Ethics

GREEK 130.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 3. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 130.title: Readings in New Testament

GREEK 131.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Topics vary from year to year and include "Longinus," On Sublime; Marcus Aurelius; Arrian; Second Sophistic; Plutarch; later epic; epigram; epistolographi Graeci. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 131.title: Readings in Later Greek

GREEK 132.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Readings based on (1) "Anthology of Byzantine Prose," ed. Nigel Wilson and (2) "Oxford Book of Medieval and Modern Greek Verse," ed. C.A. Trypanis, or if unavailable, "Poeti bizantini," ed. R. Cantarella. In addition, necessary historical and cultural background provided by readings and lectures. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 132.title: Survey of Byzantine Literature

GREEK 133.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 132. Topics vary from year to year and include Procopius, Agathias, Michael Psellus, Alexiad of Anna Comnena, and Digenis Akritas. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 133.title: Readings in Byzantine Literature

GREEK 15.description: Lecture, 18 to 19 hours. Eight-week intensive introduction to principles of speaking, reading, and writing modern (demotic) Greek. Offered in summer only. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 15.title: Elementary Modern Greek

GREEK 16.description: Lecture, 19 hours. Eight-week intensive introduction to Greek language equivalent to courses 1, 2, and 3. Offered in summer only. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 16.title: Intensive First-Year Greek

GREEK 189.description: Seminar, three hours. Limited to 20 students. Designed as adjunct to undergraduate lecture course. Exploration of topics in greater depth through supplemental readings, papers, or other activities and led by lecture course instructor. May be applied toward honors credit for eligible students. Honors content noted on transcript. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 189.title: Advanced Honors Seminars

GREEK 189HC.description: Tutorial, three hours. Limited to students in College Honors Program. Designed as adjunct to upper division lecture course. Individual study with lecture course instructor to explore topics in greater depth through supplemental readings, papers, or other activities. May be repeated for maximum of 4 units. Individual honors contract required. Honors content noted on transcript. Letter grading.
GREEK 189HC.title: Honors Contracts

GREEK 19.description: Seminar, one hour. Discussion of and critical thinking about topics of current intellectual importance, taught by faculty members in their areas of expertise and illuminating many paths of discovery at UCLA. P/NP grading.
GREEK 19.title: Fiat Lux Freshman Seminars

GREEK 197.description: Tutorial, two hours. Limited to juniors/seniors. Individual intensive study, with scheduled meetings to be arranged between faculty member and student. Assigned reading and tangible evidence of mastery of subject matter required. May be repeated for credit. Individual contract required. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 197.title: Individual Studies in Greek

GREEK 199.description: Tutorial, two hours. Limited to juniors/seniors. Supervised individual research or investigation under guidance of faculty mentor. Culminating paper or project required. May be repeated for credit. Individual contract required. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 199.title: Directed Research in Greek

GREEK 2.description: Lecture, three hours; discussion, two hours. Enforced requisite: course 1. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 2.title: Elementary Greek

GREEK 20.description: Lecture, three hours; discussion, one hour (when scheduled). Requisite: course 3 or 16. Formal review of Greek grammar and syntax and development of skills in reading original texts of Greek prose. Readings selected to introduce literature and culture of ancient Greece. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 20.title: Intermediate Greek

GREEK 200A.description: Lecture, three hours. Lectures on history of Greek literature, supplemented by reading of Greek texts in original language. May be taken independently for credit. S/U or letter grading.
GREEK 200A.title: History of Greek Literature

GREEK 200B.description: Lecture, three hours. Lectures on history of Greek literature, supplemented by reading of Greek texts in original language. May be taken independently for credit. S/U or letter grading.
GREEK 200B.title: History of Greek Literature

GREEK 200C.description: Lecture, three hours. Lectures on history of Greek literature, supplemented by reading of Greek texts in original language. May be taken independently for credit. S/U or letter grading.
GREEK 200C.title: History of Greek Literature

GREEK 201A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 201A is requisite to 201B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 201A.title: Homer: Iliad

GREEK 201B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 201A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 201B.title: Homer: Iliad

GREEK 202A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 202A is requisite to 202B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 202A.title: Homer: Odyssey and Epic Cycle

GREEK 202B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 202A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 202B.title: Homer: Odyssey and Epic Cycle

GREEK 203.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 203.title: Hesiod

GREEK 204.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 204.title: Homeric Hymns

GREEK 205.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 205.title: Aeschylus

GREEK 206A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 206A is requisite to 206B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 206A.title: Sophocles

GREEK 206B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 206A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 206B.title: Sophocles

GREEK 207A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 207A is requisite to 207B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 207A.title: Euripides

GREEK 207B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 207A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 207B.title: Euripides

GREEK 208A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 208A is requisite to 208B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 208A.title: Aristophanes

GREEK 208B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 208A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 208B.title: Aristophanes

GREEK 209A.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 209A.title: Seminar: Hellenistic Poetry

GREEK 209B.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 209B.title: Seminar: Hellenistic Poetry

GREEK 210.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 110. S/U or letter grading.
GREEK 210.title: Advanced Greek Prose Composition

GREEK 211A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 211A is requisite to 211B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 211A.title: Herodotus

GREEK 211B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 211A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 211B.title: Herodotus

GREEK 212A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 212A is requisite to 212B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 212A.title: Thucydides

GREEK 212B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 212A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 212B.title: Thucydides

GREEK 213.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 213.title: Greek Historiography

GREEK 214.description: Lecture, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 214.title: Demosthenes

GREEK 215.description: Seminar, three hours. Studies in works of Antiphon, Andocides, and Lysias. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 215.title: Early Greek Orators

GREEK 216.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 216.title: Menander

GREEK 217A.description: Seminar, three hours. Study of lyric poetry of Archaic period, both choral and monodic, with elegiac and iambic included. May be taken independently for credit. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 217A.title: Greek Lyric Poetry: Archaic Lyric

GREEK 217B.description: Seminar, three hours. Study of choral odes of Pindar and Bacchylides, with special attention to conventions of epinician. May be taken independently for credit. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 217B.title: Greek Lyric Poetry: Pindar and Bacchylides

GREEK 220.description: Seminar, three hours. Study of Greek romance and its place in Greek literature. Two texts (Chariton: "Chaereas and Callirhoe" and Longus: "Daphnis and Chloe") studied in some detail. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 220.title: Greek Novel

GREEK 221.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 221.title: Pre-Socratic Philosophers

GREEK 222A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 222A is requisite to 222B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 222A.title: Plato

GREEK 222B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 222A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 222B.title: Plato

GREEK 223A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 223A is requisite to 223B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 223A.title: Aristotle

GREEK 223B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 223A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 223B.title: Aristotle

GREEK 224.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 224.title: Post-Aristotelian Philosophy

GREEK 229.description: Seminar, three hours. Preparation: graduate-level knowledge of ancient Greek. Practice in translation of previously unseen texts from variety of authors and genres. Topics include peculiarities of style and vocabulary of distinct genres, literary versus scholarly translation, semantic properties of particular words and constructions. S/U grading.
GREEK 229.title: Sight Translation

GREEK 240A.description: Lecture, four hours. Course 240A is requisite to 240B. Linguistic history of classical Greek. S/U or letter grading.
GREEK 240A.title: History of Greek Language

GREEK 240B.description: Lecture, four hours. Requisite: course 240A. Postclassical, medieval, and modern Greek. S/U or letter grading.
GREEK 240B.title: History of Greek Language

GREEK 241.description: Seminar, three hours. Survey of Greek historical inscriptions, chiefly Attic. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 241.title: Greek Epigraphy

GREEK 242.description: Lecture, three hours. Linguistic situation in early Greece. Readings in classical Greek dialectal texts. Greek grammar in context of common Greek and Indo-European linguistics. S/U or letter grading.
GREEK 242.title: Greek Dialects and Historical Grammar

GREEK 243.description: Seminar, three hours. Script, language, and grammar of Linear B inscriptions; their relevance to ancient Greek linguistic and cultural history. S/U or letter grading.
GREEK 243.title: Mycenaean Greek

GREEK 244.description: Seminar, three hours. Preparation: reading knowledge of Greek. Introduction to Greek papyri, considered both as historical documents and as carriers of literature. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 244.title: Greek Papyrology

GREEK 245.description: Seminar, three hours. Studies in development of book hand in Greek manuscripts earlier than invention of printing. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 245.title: Greek Palaeography

GREEK 250.description: Lecture, three hours. Advanced study of some aspect of ancient Greek language, literature, and/or culture. May be repeated for credit with topic change. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
GREEK 250.title: Topical Studies of Ancient Greece

GREEK 3.description: Lecture, three hours; discussion, two hours. Enforced requisite: course 2. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 3.title: Elementary Greek

GREEK 596.description: Tutorial, to be arranged. S/U grading.
GREEK 596.title: Directed Individual Study or Research

GREEK 597.description: Tutorial, to be arranged. S/U grading.
GREEK 597.title: Study for M.A

GREEK 599.description: Tutorial, to be arranged. S/U grading.
GREEK 599.title: Research for Ph.D

GREEK 89.description: Seminar, three hours. Limited to 20 students. Designed as adjunct to lower division lecture course. Exploration of topics in greater depth through supplemental readings, papers, or other activities and led by lecture course instructor. May be applied toward honors credit for eligible students. Honors content noted on transcript. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 89.title: Honors Seminars

GREEK 89HC.description: Tutorial, three hours. Limited to students in College Honors Program. Designed as adjunct to lower division lecture course. Individual study with lecture course instructor to explore topics in greater depth through supplemental readings, papers, or other activities. May be repeated for maximum of 4 units. Individual honors contract required. Honors content noted on transcript. Letter grading.
GREEK 89HC.title: Honors Contracts

GREEK 8A.description: Lecture, three hours. Introduction to basic elements of modern Greek conversation for beginning students, including those with some knowledge of ancient (Attic) Greek. Conducted in modern Greek, with in-class conversation drills, regular homework assignments, and weekly quizzes. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 8A.title: Elementary Modern Greek

GREEK 8B.description: Lecture, three hours. Enforced requisite: course 8A. Introductory modern Greek sequence, with emphasis on spoken modern Greek. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 8B.title: Elementary Modern Greek

GREEK 8C.description: Lecture, three hours. Enforced requisite: course 8B. Introductory modern Greek sequence, with emphasis on spoken modern Greek. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 8C.title: Elementary Modern Greek

GREEK 99.description: Tutorial (supervised research or other scholarly work), three hours per week per unit. Entry-level research for lower division students under guidance of faculty mentor. Students must be in good academic standing and enrolled in minimum of 12 units (excluding this course). Individual contract required; consult Undergraduate Research Center. May be repeated. P/NP grading.
GREEK 99.title: Student Research Program

GREEK 9A.description: Lecture, three hours. Enforced requisite: course 8C. Course 9A is enforced requisite to 9B, which is enforced requisite to 9C. Intermediate-level program in modern Greek language study from communicative and task-based approach. Continued development of student understanding and use of Greek syntax and morphology through oral and written activities, reading, and listening. Students master basic communication skills, communicate in everyday real-life situations, comprehend simple passages, announcements, and advertisements, master basic rules of modern Greek grammar and syntax, read fluently, and write accurately. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 9A.title: Intermediate Modern Greek

GREEK 9B.description: Lecture, three hours. Enforced requisite: course 9A. Intermediate-level program in modern Greek language study from communicative and task-based approach. Continued development of student understanding and use of Greek syntax and morphology through oral and written activities, reading, and listening. Students master basic communication skills, communicate in everyday real-life situations, comprehend simple passages, announcements, and advertisements, master basic rules of modern Greek grammar and syntax, read fluently, and write accurately. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 9B.title: Intermediate Modern Greek

GREEK 9C.description: Lecture, three hours. Enforced requisite: course 9B. Intermediate-level program in modern Greek language study from communicative and task-based approach. Continued development of student understanding and use of Greek syntax and morphology through oral and written activities, reading, and listening. Students master basic communication skills, communicate in everyday real-life situations, comprehend simple passages, announcements, and advertisements, master basic rules of modern Greek grammar and syntax, read fluently, and write accurately. P/NP or letter grading.
GREEK 9C.title: Intermediate Modern Greek
